Born March 10, 1879, in Villa María, in Córdoba province, Del Campo exemplified the nationalist, female Argentine feminist movement at the turn of the twentieth century. She devoted her life to feminism and the fight for democratic justice—often in the face of personal oppression. Throughout her career, Del Campo successfully disobeyed masculine social norms to live up to her personal ideals and choices as a female intellectual, writer, journalist, and translator.

Claudia Salazar, Una décima mirada. Journalist Claudia Salazar wrote this ten-chapter novella in response to 600,000 people lost to violence and mass graves in Latin America. It is a harsh depiction of a brutal, paramilitary world where she throws into focus La Guerra Sucia, the Dirty War in Argentina, a front that would remain largely unknown due to government censorship and misinformation. Before she published this book, she died tragically in an accident. Abruptly, readers were not able to speak directly with her, yet some believe she was able to leave a very powerful political and cultural testament through her writing.
